    <h1>The coro&#xAD;n&#xAD;avirus oil shock</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201229/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-29"><time>2020-12-29</time></a>
        - <span>BUSINESS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>As the Covid-19 out­break shut economies world­wide, crude oil prices started their down­hill jour­ney to­wards a low that was un­think­able be­fore. And if that was not enough, the world's big­gest ex­porters of the com­mod­ity – Saudi Ara­bia and Rus­sia – had a spat over pro­duc­tion cuts, trig­ger­ing a price war. Prices nose­dived into the un­prece­dented ter­ri­tory of be­low zero dol­lars per bar­rel in April. De­mand re­cov­ery is likely to be slow and grad­ual next year.</p>

